( NOTE )   
Websites are hosted on web servers, which are normal computers that can contain multiple websites sharing the same IP address. This means your target website might not be alone on the server, and if you cannot find vulnerabilities in it, you can try attacking other websites hosted on the same server. If you successfully exploit one of them, you may gain access to the entire server and then navigate to your actual target website. Tools like Robtex or search engines can help identify other domains sharing the same IP, making this a useful strategy in penetration testing when the main target is secure.


*Discovering Subdomains

Subdomains are important in penetration testing because they expand the attack surface of a target by revealing additional entry points beyond the main domain. Each subdomain (like mail.example.com or admin.example.com) can host a completely different web application, including admin panels, internal tools, beta versions, or poorly secured services. These areas are often less tested and more likely to contain vulnerabilities or sensitive information. By discovering and analyzing subdomains using tools like Knockpy, Sublist3r, an attacker or tester increases the chances of finding weaknesses that can be exploited to gain access to the main website or even the entire server.

